Description: Obligation of “Jusquinus des pres”, cleric of the diocese of Cambrai, to Sebastianus de Ursis, priest of the diocese of Aix-en-Provence, concerning permutation of benefices in Lamotte (diocese of Toul: one of René of Anjou’s own chapels there) and in Puy-St-Reparade (diocese of Aix). More likely to be 1476, since 19 Feb was a Sunday in 1475 but a Tuesday in 1476.

Jean Michel writes to Sigismondo d'Este from Asti, where he is a soldier for Alfonso I d'Este. He promises to bring Sigismondo some new music, and notes that Hilaire Turluron is going to France to bring back singers.

Letter from Giovanni Tommaso Manfredi to Cardinal Ippolito I d'Este. Jacotin, a soprano, is in the service of the Cardinal of Aragon, but wants to come to Ferrara. Turluron and Zoan Francesco (da Lodi? da Padua?) suggested a new sorpano, who is viewed as the new Bidon. But Manfredi did not want to hire him unless he was approved by Carpentras.
Letter from Jean Michel to Sigismondo d'Este from Vigevano, the location of Francis I.
Letter from Jean Michel to Sigismondo d'Este from Vigevano, the location of Francis I.
Letter from Jean Michel to Sigismondo d'Este from Milan.
Letter from Enea Pio to Cardinal Ippolito I d'Este from Rome, noting that he cannot find Tuluron, but has asked Carpentras to let Tuluron know that he has something to discuss with him.

Letter from Enea Pio to Carinal Ippolito I d'Este. Pio has spoken with Tuluron, who told him that Jacotin Frontin has left for France about a month-and-a-half ago to become the master of the chapel of Francis I.
MInute of ducal letter to Bartolomeo de' Cavalieri

Letter from Antonio Colobaudi (Bidon) to Alfonso I d'Este. Bidon wants to renounce a benefice in the Ferrarese territory at San Leonardo in favor of his son Gasparino, and to renounce it with the right of regression. He wants this done before he departs Rome, as the pope will do it as a favor to Bidon as a farewelll gift. Finishing the transfer will save Bidon 200 ducats. Bidon asks for letters from Alfonso and Ippolito saying that he will never be deprived of his salary during his lifetime. (Lockwood, p. 231)
Letter from Aldrovandini Sacrati to Duke Alfonso I d'Este. Jean Mouton has gone to Paris; Sacrati will be resident commissioner for Alfonso

Letter from Aldrovandini Sacrati to Duke Alfonso I d'Este. Jean Mouton has gone to Paris to write some new works in honor of the birth of the Dauphin; Sacrati will be with Mouton soon, and Mouton has promised to give him new works
Letter from Aldrovandini Sacrati to Duke Alfonso I d'Este. Jean Mouton has not yet returned from Paris, so Sacrati has not received any new works yet.

Letter from Aldrovandini Sacrati to Duke Alfonso I d'Este. Jean Mouton has returned from Paris and Sacrati is now sending Alfonso new music by Mouton, including a motet. Mouton has written a piece for the birth of the Dauphin and will give Sacrati more pieces on a daily basis.
Letter from Aldrovandini Sacrati to Duke Alfonso I d'Este. Sacrati encloses a motet given to him by Mouton, who says that he will soon give him another composition.

Letter from Aldrovandini Sacrati to Duke Alfonso I d'Este. Mouton and a soprano of the royal chapel named Comon were at supper with Sacrati. Mouton brought with him the attached pieces (four folios + half on another folio). Sacrati says that it is a new piece, but that Sacrati has heard it before at the king's table. Mouton says that he hasn't copied it before and begs the duke not to give it to anyone else. Mouton was sent today to Picardy and it is not known when he will return
Letter from Carlo da Correggio to Duke Alfonso I. Encloses a mass and motet by Longueval. Longueval and Mouton are not at the court, but if Mouton returns, Correggio will try to acquire some pieces.
Letter from Enea Pio to Ippolito I d'Este, describing that the contrabass Jean de la Fage sings well
